  <h3>Counseling on retainer</h3>
  <p>Every team is made of people, and every person hits a hard season eventually. A marriage strains. A parent gets sick. Confidence takes a hit and doesn't bounce back on schedule. Most companies find out about a hard season late, after it has already shown up in the work. Some decide to have support standing ready instead.</p>
  <p>Here's how it works. The company puts time on retainer. Employees book directly with me, and nobody has to explain to a manager why they want a session. From there, the shape fits the person. For some companies, sessions run on a steady rhythm — every other week or once a month — and support is simply a normal part of working life. For others, the retainer is there for the seasons: someone going through something hard meets with me weekly for a month or two, works through it, and then doesn't need me again until life says otherwise.</p>
  <p>And the sessions are confidential. The company pays for the time. What's said in it belongs to the employee. That's not a courtesy — it's the reason this works. People only bring the real thing into a room they trust.</p>

  <h3>Why companies do it</h3>
  <p>People rarely announce a hard season. It shows up sideways: the reliable one gets quiet, the sharp one gets short, the steady one starts missing things. By the time it reaches a manager's desk, it's usually been running for months. By the time it reaches a resignation letter, the chance to help has passed.</p>
  <p>A retainer changes the timing. Struggles get support early, while they're still small and still private. People steady out faster, because nobody has to wait for things to get bad enough to justify asking for help. Burnout loses its foothold, because the load gets shared before it crushes anyone. And managers get to stay managers, because when someone on the team is struggling, there's somewhere real for it to go.</p>
  <p>Something else happens too, deeper than logistics. People are loyal to what invests in them. When a company stands by someone through a hard season, that person invests back — in the work, in the team, in the company that didn't look away.</p>
  <p>One boundary, named plainly: this is steady, preventative support, not crisis care. The whole design is to reach hard seasons early, so they never become crises at all.</p>

  <h3>Team repair</h3>
  <p>Sometimes the problem isn't a person going through something. It's two people, or a whole team, stuck in how they see each other. A conflict that keeps resurfacing no matter how many times it's been declared resolved. Two key people who can't work together and need to. A team that has quietly reorganized itself around avoiding someone.</p>
  <p>When that happens, I come in and help. I listen to each side separately first, because people tell the truth differently when the other person isn't in the room. Then we find what each person is actually reacting to — which is rarely the thing being argued about. We bring the interpretations into the open, check them against each other, and rebuild the working agreements from there.</p>
  <p>What I find, almost every time: the personality conflict isn't a personality conflict. It's two reasonable interpretations that never got checked. Once they're checked, the heat goes out of it, and the team gets back to the work.</p>
